Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as d67b2627fd1d16ad96866c6288d54bcf63a992e3
not much details provided to understand why this interface is added
Agreed, the related commit has much more detail that perhaps this should also copy over: https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-debug-collector/+/53017
Added more details to the commit message.
This interface is already defined undet Entry, rename to type?
Sure, done.
Better to add possible "errors:" details.
I'm not sure yet what errors would be associated with these properties. Is it ok to add them later as needed?
To be added later as needed.
Are you expecting these properties to be 'readonly'?  'const'?
Done
Types should not be an arbitrary string.  Please define enumerations or a mechanism for system-specific enumerations (depending on what you're trying to encapsulate).
Done
By the way, what would be an example of system-specific enumerations?
I'm not a big fan of this property name.  What have we used in other dumps to represent the path to the associated log?  Is it an association or a property?

From what I see, other phosphor-debug-collector dump entries aren't currently referencing logs from other daemons.

I changed directions a bit in patchset 6 (please see the new MainLogRef description). What I'm now trying to do for the two initial types of fault data is to supply the reference as the log ID string needed by the dbus client (bmcweb) to construct the redfish URI to the log. The ID isn't always in the dbus object path, and I'm trying to add it as a property here to avoid extra dbus calls to look up the ID.

Feel free to suggest a better name or approach if you have one in mind.

>> From what I see, other phosphor-debug-collector dump entries aren't currently referencing logs from other daemons.

Oh I take it back, there is a "SourceDumpId" property in the xyz.openbmc_project.Dump.Entry.System interface referring to an associated log.

(The type and usage of the property are a bit different from the FaultLog use case though, so I figure I shouldn't make the names very similar.)

>> From what I see, other phosphor-debug-collector dump entries aren't currently referencing logs from other daemons.

Oh, I take it back, there is a "SourceDumpId" property in xyz.openbmc_project.Dump.Entry.System.interface.yaml referring to an associated log.

In which cases do we have either of these?  I don't know how a client can tell the difference.

If it is a dbus object_path then use object_path and not string.
Updated the description, please take a look.
Removing SupplementalLogRefs for now -- will consider it to be future work.
Why is it called 'MainLogRef'?  That seems like an unusual name.
How about MainLogId? Updated the description to say that "Main" is in contrast to "Supplemental".
Can it be PrimaryID and SecondaryID?  Is "Main" and "Supplemental" coming from some standard elsewhere we are trying to follow?  Will Secondary/Supplemental IDs be a list?

"Primary"/"Secondary" are fine with me; we are not bound to a particular standard. Are you okay with "PrimaryLogId" and "SecondaryLogId" to be a little more descriptive of what the Id is for?

Yes I'm thinking Secondary IDs would be a list. Maybe a list of pairs of type and ID. (I think we should wait to add it in a future separate code review because we don't have the details of the use case all figured out yet.)
Ack

Are you intending that these are only used by humans or is there suppose to be some utility of it internal to the BMC?  General for arbitrary strings we include some verbiage about it not being programmatically interrogated.
Please see my previous comment at https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/53018/comments/82cb3b7e_d15d717f about the bmcweb use case I have in mind.

The link is meant to point to the comment thread at Patchset 4, line 9 of yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Dump/Entry/FaultLog.interface.yaml:

"I changed directions a bit in patchset 6 (please see the new MainLogRef description). What I'm now trying to do for the two initial types of fault data is to supply the reference as the log ID string needed by the dbus client (bmcweb) to construct the redfish URI to the log. The ID isn't always in the dbus object path, and I'm trying to add it as a property here to avoid extra dbus calls to look up the ID."
Updated description as we discussed over discord.
Can we re-render this to not be a table and have huge line wrapping?  Maybe these belong nearby the enums?
Removed table.
Is "crashdump" standard terminology or is it relevant to only a certain processor manufacturer?

It's pretty standard:  Here's an instance of the kernel using it for "kernel crash dump"

https://ubuntu.com/server/docs/kernel-crash-dump
I guess I have concern about disambiguation then.  Are we talking about kdumps or are we talking about a collection of processor data?

We're talking about a collection of processor data (chipset dump)."Crashdump" seems to be becoming the standard term these days. From what I've heard, collecting kernel dumps isn't as common nowadays because of PII and security concerns. But if we end up needing to differentiate them, I think we could consider "kernel dump" and "chipset dump" to be subtypes of "crashdump".

Aren't they two totally different things though?  It seems like they would warrant their own type?  My current unsettledness with it is that I believe you are talking about what Intel has traditionally called 'crashdump'.  I'm not positive if AMD uses that same terminology and have more doubts about IBM and ARM-based platforms using that terminology, so it sort of becomes architecture-specific.  We tend to avoid architecture-specific enumerations in xyz.openbmc_project and instead place them in, for example, com.intel.

Yes kernel dump and chipset dump (e.g. Intel Crashdump) are totally different things that happen to use the same "Crashdump" term. The term "Crashdump" seems to be gaining traction in the industry for describing a chipset dump at crash, for example AMD uses the term as well, but I don't know about IBM and ARM. To address the concerns about ambiguity and being too architecture-specific, what do you think of "ChipsetCrashdump" or "ChipsetDump" as the property name?

@AndrewG, @AndrewJ, @Jayanth - Can one of you give color on this from IBM's perspective?

@Thang, @Thu - Can one of you give insight into ARM/Ampere?

We just tend to call it a Hardware dump (https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/com/ibm/Dump/Entry/Hardware.interface.yaml). I tend to associated "crash dump" with a kdump (but I don't do much in the x86/amd space).

Based on this doc it seems like Arm calls it "crash dump" or "scan dump".  "scan dump" is certainly a term I remember it being called at IBM.  Intel, from my observations, uses "crash dump".

https://documentation-service.arm.com/static/5fb7e810ca04df4095c1d658?token=

Unless we can point to a documented term in a standard (like Redfish), I'd prefer we use something more generic named but still obvious what it is.  "Crashdump" seems ambiguous.  At a minimum we should document in the description what we're talking about so we don't lead anyone astray.
Updated property name and description.
I am sorry for slow response. We still not have consistent definition for crashdump and still in discussion
Ampere Crash Dump is basically a Chipset Dump at crash that contains CPU and coprocessor register status and information.

Thanks all for the input. Patrick, what do you think?

If we're unable to agree on a generic type name for chipset crashdumps, then another option is to allow an enum value of "OEM" for Type, and use that in conjunction with the "AdditionalTypeName" string for company-specific types.

Other than IBM it seems like everyone uses (or at least understands) Crashdump.  Please add a bit more words to the description to clarify what it is (for anyone who might run across it and not know) and then we are good to merge this.

Given that ChipsetCrashdumps don't use a single standardized format across companies, we probably need a way to indicate which company's ChipsetCrashdump we're referring to, for dump parsing purposes.
